WEBVTT

03:20.950 --> 03:25.454
(Italian-accented man)
My father was a very big man.

03:25.538 --> 03:30.042
All his life he wore a black moustache.

03:30.126 --> 03:35.005
When it turned grey
he used a little brush to keep it black,

03:35.089 --> 03:39.676
such as ladies use
for their eyes - mascara.

03:39.761 --> 03:45.641
Everyone was afraid of him.
My mother, my four sisters.

03:45.725 --> 03:52.189
At the dining table you could not speak
unless spoken to first by my father.

03:52.273 --> 03:56.568
But he loved me.
I was his favourite.

04:48.329 --> 04:50.789
(woman) I want to call England.

04:50.873 --> 04:52.874
Yes, I want to call England.

04:54.252 --> 04:56.712
No, it's not London.

04:57.797 --> 04:59.881
It's not London.

05:01.592 --> 05:05.554
It's in Sussex. Hastings in Sussex.

05:05.638 --> 05:08.390
You know the code.
You got it for me yesterday.

05:08.474 --> 05:10.851
Well, someone did, yes.

05:10.935 --> 05:15.605
Quattro cinque otto due sei uno.

05:15.690 --> 05:17.774
Hastings, Sussex.

05:19.360 --> 05:21.737
Oh, God!

05:24.741 --> 05:28.035
Can't read this damn book. It's...

05:28.119 --> 05:30.203
It's unreadable.

05:31.331 --> 05:36.752
Can't even bind the bloody thing properly.
Come on, let's go out.

05:36.878 --> 05:42.382
- I'm trying to get through to the children.
- All right. Answer.

05:43.134 --> 05:45.218
Hello. Yes.

05:46.721 --> 05:49.014
Mother, hello!

05:49.098 --> 05:51.600
Yes, lovely.

05:53.144 --> 05:56.480
Yes, absolutely. How are they?

05:58.232 --> 06:00.192
Are they...?

06:00.276 --> 06:02.361
Yes, lovely.

06:03.029 --> 06:05.489
Hello, darling, it's Mummy.

06:05.948 --> 06:08.033
How are you?

06:09.160 --> 06:11.244
Is Cathy there?

06:59.585 --> 07:01.670
(rustling)

07:08.094 --> 07:10.178
Incredible, isn't it?

07:29.866 --> 07:33.535
I think the St Augustine is incredible.

07:33.619 --> 07:35.245
So...

07:36.914 --> 07:40.834
- I don't know.
- Mm. You thought that the last time.

07:41.711 --> 07:43.170
What do you mean?

07:43.254 --> 07:46.882
You thought that the last time
we were in Venice, remember?

07:46.966 --> 07:48.675
Did I?

07:48.759 --> 07:51.511
- Well, so what?
- Nothing, I'm just...

07:51.596 --> 07:55.390
What's the point of saying that?
Why did you say that?

07:55.433 --> 07:59.019
- I didn't mean it as an insult.
- Christ.

07:59.103 --> 08:02.105
- I'm making an observation.
- What observation?

08:02.190 --> 08:06.568
I'm simply pointing out
you haven't changed your mind.

08:06.652 --> 08:08.820
(camera shutter clicks)

08:09.822 --> 08:14.493
Anyway, I agree with you.
I think it's incredible too.

09:28.568 --> 09:30.235
Shit!

09:31.320 --> 09:33.738
What is it?

09:33.823 --> 09:35.490
Look.

09:37.118 --> 09:39.411
Got another pimple.

09:40.663 --> 09:43.873
Tsk! The girls won't love you any more.

09:46.252 --> 09:49.462
- I must need more salt or something.
- What?

09:49.547 --> 09:52.716
I must need to eat more salt or something.

09:52.800 --> 09:55.844
You don't need salt, you need sex.

09:55.928 --> 09:57.929
Hmph!

09:58.014 --> 10:01.141
- Could I have it with salt?
- Why not?

10:01.934 --> 10:03.893
(phone rings)

10:03.978 --> 10:07.522
God! Don't they know I'm trying to shave?

10:14.572 --> 10:16.823
Hello?

10:16.907 --> 10:20.660
Yes, he is. Hold on a minute.
It's Simon.

10:27.126 --> 10:29.002
What?

10:29.086 --> 10:35.300
I'm only halfway through the bloody thing.
It's unreadable anyway.

10:35.384 --> 10:38.845
This is supposed to be my holiday.

10:46.103 --> 10:48.605
- Those two. Thank you.
- Ventimila.

10:52.568 --> 10:54.653
Ecco una.

10:54.737 --> 10:56.821
This one's for Jack.

10:57.907 --> 11:01.785
- Ecco la seconda.
- And this is for Cathy. What do you think?

11:01.869 --> 11:03.870
They'll be thrilled.

11:03.954 --> 11:07.916
I'm going to do a little drawing of Cathy.

11:08.542 --> 11:10.627
With spots.

11:11.545 --> 11:14.464
And I'm going to do
a little drawing of Jack.

11:14.548 --> 11:16.633
(woman laughs)

11:18.010 --> 11:19.678
For Jack.

11:19.762 --> 11:21.388
Jacko.

11:21.889 --> 11:26.059
- What do you think?
- Fantastic. You're a genius.

11:26.185 --> 11:28.269
Grazie.

11:35.194 --> 11:37.278
Hold it.

11:37.738 --> 11:40.031
Oh, come on. Smile!

11:43.577 --> 11:46.830
- Would you take a photograph of us?
- Avec plaisir.

11:46.914 --> 11:48.998
Thank you.

11:50.543 --> 11:52.627
Tiens-moi ga.

11:59.802 --> 12:01.344
Voilà.

12:01.429 --> 12:03.513
Thank you.

12:19.196 --> 12:25.493
(man) My youngest sisters, Alice and
Lisa, came to me in the garden and said:

12:25.578 --> 12:29.122
"Robert, Robert,
come to the kitchen quickly."

12:29.206 --> 12:32.751
"Eva and Maria have a treat for you."

12:46.974 --> 12:50.018
(woman) Cathy's been selected
for the football team.

12:50.102 --> 12:54.856
- (man) What football team?
- The school football team. What else?

12:55.900 --> 12:59.652
- (woman) Don't you think it's dangerous?
- Not really.

12:59.737 --> 13:05.241
(woman) Tell me something.
Tell me the truth. Do you like children?

13:05.326 --> 13:08.036
- What children?
- My children.

13:10.581 --> 13:13.124
I like your children.

13:13.209 --> 13:18.004
No, what I mean is,
do you actually like children?

13:18.088 --> 13:24.010
- You mean all children?
- Children. Do you actually like children?

13:24.094 --> 13:27.472
You mean as such?
The species as such?

13:30.267 --> 13:32.769
What I mean is...

13:32.853 --> 13:37.065
The real truth is...
you don't like children.

13:39.485 --> 13:43.446
What you mean is,
you think I don't like your children.

13:47.493 --> 13:49.577
What about me?

13:51.622 --> 13:54.249
Do you like me?

13:57.044 --> 13:59.128
I like you.

14:00.673 --> 14:03.132
And you know why?

14:03.217 --> 14:04.884
NO,

14:04.969 --> 14:10.181
I like you because you're always
asking me such challenging questions.

14:10.266 --> 14:13.309
You're always testing my intellect.

14:42.214 --> 14:46.885
Did I ever tell you the terrible thing that
happened to me when I was a little girl?

14:46.969 --> 14:50.597
The worst thing
that ever happened to me?

14:50.681 --> 14:53.308
No, you didn't tell me.

14:53.392 --> 14:58.938
Well, I was about seven or eight and...

14:59.023 --> 15:05.904
there was this gang of kids,
boys and girls, and we were this gang.

15:09.867 --> 15:11.951
One day...

15:12.912 --> 15:18.166
some of them said "One member of this
gang isn't good enough to be a member."

15:18.250 --> 15:21.961
"Does everyone agree that
we should throw this person out?"

15:22.046 --> 15:26.299
And I said "Yes." I clapped.

15:26.383 --> 15:28.051
Clapped?

15:28.135 --> 15:29.802
Yes.

15:32.348 --> 15:38.478
I clapped. I said
"Yes, throw this person out."

15:39.939 --> 15:42.815
And you know who that person was?

15:45.694 --> 15:47.362
You.

15:48.781 --> 15:50.448
Yes.

15:52.910 --> 15:54.994
That's terrible.

15:56.121 --> 15:58.831
(both laugh) That's a terrible story.

16:06.924 --> 16:09.842
Up at dawn for you and into a speedboat.

16:09.927 --> 16:12.345
Where shall we go?
Where can we go?

16:12.429 --> 16:15.807
Murano. They blow beautiful glass.
Very nice.

16:15.891 --> 16:18.851
Murano! Lovely.

16:18.936 --> 16:21.312
- What time's dawn?
- Dawn, signore?

16:21.397 --> 16:25.900
Daybreak.
A speedboat to Murano at daybreak.

16:37.746 --> 16:42.250
And on the table were two big
bottles of lemonade, a cream cake,

16:42.334 --> 16:47.046
two packets of cooking chocolate,
a big box of marshmallows.

16:47.131 --> 16:51.592
And Maria said
"Look, darling. This is all for you."

17:25.335 --> 17:27.211
(woman) Colin?

17:32.885 --> 17:34.969
Find anything?

17:39.725 --> 17:41.809
Isn't this beautiful?

17:48.275 --> 17:50.359
What do you think?

18:10.047 --> 18:15.301
And Maria said "Look, darling.
This is all for you."

18:51.547 --> 18:53.005
(woman groans)

18:53.090 --> 18:55.049
Are you asleep?

18:55.134 --> 18:57.218
Mary, it's late.

18:58.011 --> 19:01.013
- What is it?
- We haven't had any dinner.

19:01.098 --> 19:03.182
What time is it?

19:04.268 --> 19:05.893
Late.

19:07.354 --> 19:09.730
Will Padovani's be open?

19:09.815 --> 19:12.859
- Or what about...?
- No. It's quite late.

19:12.943 --> 19:14.944
Too late. All closed.

19:15.028 --> 19:18.698
But I know a very good bar.
Late-night bar.

19:18.782 --> 19:24.579
Nice sandwich. Good drinks.
Very nice place. Very easy to find.

19:24.663 --> 19:30.459
- All right. We'll have to take a map.
- All out. It's my only one, sorry.

19:30.544 --> 19:34.881
- Let me look.
- Here. You see? Very nice.

19:34.965 --> 19:40.219
You go straight out of here.
Turn and take a right.

19:40.304 --> 19:43.514
Then you turn and take a right.

19:43.599 --> 19:45.892
Right there.

19:47.019 --> 19:50.146
Right. Thanks.

20:30.771 --> 20:33.689
- Look, this way.
- How do you know?

21:09.977 --> 21:12.061
What do you think?

21:30.914 --> 21:36.043
- Yes, there we are.
- No. It's definitely this way.

21:36.128 --> 21:38.212
I'm sorry, but it is.

21:48.557 --> 21:50.641
(Mary groans)

21:55.022 --> 21:57.398
- This way?
- All right.

21:58.108 --> 21:59.817
Colin...

22:05.490 --> 22:07.575
What's that?

22:08.618 --> 22:10.911
(Colin laughs)

22:10.996 --> 22:13.497
(Mary) Look at that bed.

22:23.800 --> 22:29.096
- She reminds me of someone.
- It's like a space shuttle.

22:29.181 --> 22:31.891
What do you think? Where are we?

22:32.809 --> 22:34.727
Is this right?

22:34.811 --> 22:36.896
Yes, definitely.

22:40.650 --> 22:45.571
- Look at all this.
- Collettivo Femminista Venezia.

22:45.655 --> 22:49.492
- Women are so radical here.
- I wish we had a map.

22:49.576 --> 22:53.537
They want convicted rapists castrated.

22:55.290 --> 22:57.375
See this building?

22:58.919 --> 23:02.171
We've been past this building
about ten minutes ago.

23:02.255 --> 23:04.507
Quite right too.

23:04.591 --> 23:07.385
- What is?
- To castrate rapists.

23:26.571 --> 23:29.365
What was that man doing?

23:29.449 --> 23:31.617
Glass at this time of night?

23:31.701 --> 23:33.994
- Come on.
- Very strange.

23:39.918 --> 23:43.546
- I'm starving.
- I think we're on the right track.

23:43.630 --> 23:45.714
So do I.

23:46.550 --> 23:48.717
Good evening. You need help?

23:50.303 --> 23:51.971
Well...

23:52.973 --> 23:55.933
We're looking for a place
to get something to eat.

23:56.017 --> 24:01.063
There's nothing in that direction, but I can
show you a very good place that way.

24:01.148 --> 24:06.819
- Isn't there a bar just over there?
- No. Everything is closed.

24:06.903 --> 24:09.613
- My name is Robert.
- Hello.

24:09.698 --> 24:13.909
- Like to eat some beautiful food?
- We'd love to.

24:13.994 --> 24:19.498
I'll show you this place.
You must both be terribly hungry.

24:19.583 --> 24:21.917
All right. Let's go.

24:24.754 --> 24:27.256
This is Mary. I'm Colin.

24:28.091 --> 24:29.967
- You're English?
- Yes.

24:30.051 --> 24:31.719
Whereabouts?

24:31.803 --> 24:34.847
Mary's from Bristol and I'm from London.

24:34.931 --> 24:37.475
Beautiful country.

24:37.559 --> 24:40.352
- Your first trip here?
- We came three years ago.

24:40.437 --> 24:43.522
- Two years ago.
- Two.

24:43.607 --> 24:46.192
- Changed much, has it?
- Mm...

24:49.946 --> 24:52.656
These posters are everywhere.

24:53.783 --> 24:57.077
These are women who can't find a man.

24:57.162 --> 25:01.457
They want to destroy everything
that's good between men and women.

25:01.583 --> 25:04.502
They don't know what they want.

25:06.880 --> 25:08.964
This way.

25:18.308 --> 25:22.144
- Ciao, ragazzi. Come va?
- Bene, grazie.

25:30.946 --> 25:33.781
It's very easy to get lost.

25:33.865 --> 25:36.867
Often there's a dead end or a canal.

25:37.619 --> 25:39.703
(laughs)

25:42.290 --> 25:44.375
It's not far.

26:21.246 --> 26:23.205
Buona sera, Robert.

26:23.290 --> 26:24.957
Please.

26:29.212 --> 26:32.631
Monica. Jocelyn. Ça va.

26:36.636 --> 26:38.721
This way, please.

26:58.074 --> 27:00.326
It's the real Venice.

27:04.080 --> 27:06.165
Excuse me.

27:19.596 --> 27:23.223
There's no food. I'm sorry.
The cook is sick.

27:23.266 --> 27:27.728
It's a tragedy. I could kill him.
Very sorry.

27:27.812 --> 27:32.191
But this is a wonderful wine.
Full of nourishment.

27:39.240 --> 27:41.325
- Cheers.
- Cheers.

27:45.038 --> 27:47.498
Now, tell me.

27:47.582 --> 27:51.377
I'm a man of immense curiosity.
Passionate curiosity.

27:51.419 --> 27:53.170
- Are you married?
- No.

27:53.254 --> 27:56.298
- But you live together in sin.
- No.

27:56.383 --> 27:58.926
Why not? No one would stop you.

27:59.010 --> 28:02.054
In this day and age
there are no standards.

28:02.138 --> 28:07.351
What about you? Tell us a bit about you.
I mean... who are you, anyway?

28:09.270 --> 28:12.898
But you have a child. Am I right?

28:12.982 --> 28:15.067
- How did you know?
- I feel it.

28:16.027 --> 28:18.529
I have two children.

28:18.655 --> 28:20.739
A boy and a girl.

28:28.415 --> 28:30.958
- This is your boy and your girl.
- Yes.

28:31.960 --> 28:33.961
Beautiful.

28:34.045 --> 28:36.130
Not yours.

28:36.214 --> 28:38.048
Not mine.

28:39.759 --> 28:45.305
Beautiful children.
They take after their beautiful mother.

28:46.141 --> 28:49.226
Your English is terribly good.

28:49.728 --> 28:53.105
I grew up in London. My wife is Canadian.

28:53.189 --> 28:55.566
Any more breadsticks?

28:55.650 --> 28:58.360
- Ancora vino. E dei grissini.
- Arrivo subito.

28:58.445 --> 29:02.614
- Your wife's Canadian?
- Certainly. We lived there.

29:03.366 --> 29:05.451
How did you meet?

29:06.453 --> 29:10.956
That's impossible to explain without
describing my mother and sisters

29:11.040 --> 29:14.251
and that would only make sense
if I described my father.

29:14.335 --> 29:19.506
In order to explain how I met my wife
I would have to describe my father.

29:19.591 --> 29:24.011
Would you really like me to do that?
Shall I do that?

29:24.095 --> 29:29.433
- All right.
- My father was a... very big man.

29:30.477 --> 29:34.271
All his life he wore a black moustache.

29:34.355 --> 29:38.066
When it turned grey
he used a little brush to keep it black,

29:38.151 --> 29:41.320
such as ladies use
for their eyes - mascara.

29:41.404 --> 29:45.783
Everyone was afraid of him.
My mother, my four sisters.

29:45.867 --> 29:50.370
At the dining table you could not speak
unless spoken to first by my father.

29:50.455 --> 29:53.749
But he loved me.
I was his favourite.

29:54.292 --> 30:00.172
He was a diplomat all his life.
We spent years in London. Knightsbridge.

30:00.256 --> 30:05.469
Every morning he got out of bed at six
and went to the bathroom to shave.

30:05.553 --> 30:09.014
No one was allowed out of bed
until he'd finished.

30:09.057 --> 30:13.435
My eldest sisters were 14, 15. I was 10.

30:13.520 --> 30:17.147
One weekend the house was empty
for the whole afternoon.

30:17.232 --> 30:20.901
My sisters whispered together.
Their names were Eva and Maria.

30:20.985 --> 30:24.571
They called me and they led me
into my parents' bedroom.

30:24.656 --> 30:28.158
They told me to sit
on the bed and be quiet.

30:28.243 --> 30:31.703
They went to my mother's dressing table.

30:32.539 --> 30:38.126
They painted their fingernails, they put
powder on their faces, they used lipstick.

30:38.211 --> 30:42.589
They pulled hairs from their eyebrows
and brushed mascara on their lashes.

30:42.674 --> 30:47.469
(laughs) They took off their socks and put
on my mother's silk stockings, panties.

30:47.554 --> 30:54.351
They sauntered about the room looking
at the mirror, like beautiful women.

30:54.435 --> 31:00.691
They laughed and kissed, they stroked
each other, they giggled. I was enchanted.

31:00.775 --> 31:02.860
They fed my enchantment.

31:02.944 --> 31:05.904
(romantic ballad)

31:05.989 --> 31:09.491
They whispered to me
that it was our secret,

31:09.534 --> 31:14.705
that we would keep it in our hearts
forever, never reveal it.

31:14.747 --> 31:20.878
But that night at dinner I felt my father
staring at me, staring deep into me.

31:20.962 --> 31:25.841
He chewed, swallowed, he put his
knife and fork down. He looked at me.

31:25.925 --> 31:29.761
My heart started to beat.
To thump, not to beat.

31:30.513 --> 31:35.434
My father said "Tell me, Robert. What
have you been doing this afternoon?"

31:35.518 --> 31:37.978
He knew.

31:38.062 --> 31:41.773
I knew he knew.
He was God. He was testing me.

31:41.858 --> 31:48.113
So I told him. I told him all that my sisters
had done. I told him everything.

31:49.407 --> 31:55.537
My mother was silent. My sisters'
faces were white. No one spoke.

31:57.040 --> 32:00.250
My father said "Thank you."
Finished his dinner.

32:00.335 --> 32:04.922
After dinner my sisters and I
were called to my father's study.

32:05.006 --> 32:11.011
They were beaten with a leather belt
without mercy. I watched this.

32:11.054 --> 32:14.681
A month later they took their revenge.

32:14.766 --> 32:20.103
We children were again alone
in the house. Nanny was away.

32:20.188 --> 32:22.147
My youngest sisters...

32:22.231 --> 32:24.066
Grazie.

32:24.150 --> 32:27.736
...Alice and Lisa
came to me in the garden.

32:28.613 --> 32:33.909
They said "Robert, come to the kitchen.
Eva and Maria have a treat for you."

32:33.993 --> 32:36.411
I was suspicious, but I went.

32:36.496 --> 32:39.164
I was so...

32:39.207 --> 32:40.749
innocent.

32:40.833 --> 32:44.336
On the table were two big bottles
of lemonade, cream cake,

32:44.420 --> 32:47.130
cooking chocolate,
big box of marshmallows,

32:47.215 --> 32:49.841
and Maria said
"Look, this is all for you."

32:49.926 --> 32:53.136
"But first" Eva said
"you must drink some medicine."

32:53.221 --> 33:01.228
"This is very rich food and it will protect
your stomach. Help you to enjoy it."

33:01.312 --> 33:05.357
I was too greedy to question this.
I drank the medicine.

33:05.441 --> 33:09.569
Then I ate the chocolate and the cake
and drank a bottle of lemonade.

33:09.654 --> 33:14.366
They applauded and said that only a man
could drink a second bottle of lemonade.

33:14.450 --> 33:19.705
It would be beyond my capabilities.
I said "Give it to me."

33:19.789 --> 33:25.127
I drank the second bottle and I finished
the chocolate, marshmallows and cake.

33:25.211 --> 33:30.215
They said "Bravo", then
the kitchen began to spin round me

33:30.299 --> 33:34.011
and I badly needed to go
to the lavatory.

33:35.596 --> 33:38.849
Suddenly Eva and Maria held me down

33:38.933 --> 33:42.936
and tied my hands together
with a long piece of rope behind my back

33:43.021 --> 33:47.065
and dragged me into my father's study.

33:47.150 --> 33:51.236
They took the key from the inside,
slammed the door and locked it.

33:51.320 --> 33:58.285
"Bye-bye, Robert" they called.
"Now you are big Papa in his study."

33:58.369 --> 34:04.499
I was locked in my revered,
my feared father's study

34:04.584 --> 34:09.045
where he received the diplomatic corps
of London, the elite of the world.

34:09.130 --> 34:15.469
And I puked and pissed and shat
all over my father's carpets and walls.

34:15.553 --> 34:19.514
My father found me there.
He said "Robert..."

34:23.811 --> 34:26.396
"Have you been eating chocolate?"

34:26.481 --> 34:32.194
Then he nearly killed me. Then
he didn't speak to me for six months.

34:34.072 --> 34:36.864
I've never forgiven my sisters.

34:39.034 --> 34:42.036
My only solace was my mother.

